******
[2] Scotland, a single case
Date: Wed 13 Feb 2019
Source: Herald Scotland [abridged, edited]
https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17429218.first-equine-flu-case-identified-in-scotland/


A stable has gone into lockdown after the 1st case of equine flu in Scotland was identified among one of its animals.

Giorgia Burns Eventing yard in Lanarkshire implemented a quarantine after a horse arrived at the yard showing signs of the disease. Vets later confirmed the unvaccinated animal had contracted the virus, prompting the stable's owner, Giorgia Burns, to isolate the horse and begin disinfecting the yard. No other horses at the yard have shown signs of the disease.

The confirmed case comes on the day British horseracing re-opens after a 6-day shutdown following the outbreak. Two infected horses in England have had to be put down, and the British Horse Authority has introduced stringent new vaccination requirements to halt the spread of the disease.

Ms Burns said that the horse had arrived at her yard with a runny nose last Wednesday [6 Feb 2019], one of the classic symptoms of the disease.

She said: "We called the vet in straight away, but I was optimistic that it wasn't equine flu. We went into lockdown as a precaution anyway, with no horses coming in or out.

"It's now been confirmed that it is the flu, so we've had the vets back to re-vaccinate the rest of our horses and have been carrying out a deep clean of the stables as we are supposed to do. We expect to be given the all-clear next week [week of Mon 18 Feb 2019], so it will only be a 2-week shutdown. I'm just grateful this happened at this time of the year and not at the peak of the season."

She broke the news on Facebook, saying, "We have followed a strict disinfectant and quarantine regime, and any yards I went to I either went 1st thing in the morning or last thing at night after a shower and change of clothes and shoes. I have decided after today's [Thu 14 Feb 2019] results I will now take further precautions and not leave my own yard until it's all resolved. Anyone who knows me will know how devastated I am and the huge financial and emotional strain this has put on me."

The infected horse originally came from the Turlood Stables in Lesmahagow, owned by Billy and Katy Stewart. However, Mrs Stewart said the horse had been checked by a vet before leaving and had been clear of the virus, but she was uncertain when it had left her yard. "There is no flu on our yard," she said.

[Byline: Jody Harrison]

